\begin{IDEA}
**Title: Disentangling Convergence Drivers: Capital Deepening vs. TFP Catch-up in Endogenous Growth Regimes**

This research quantifies the relative contributions of capital deepening and TFP convergence to the economic growth of 50 countries between 1990 and 2019. By applying a panel growth accounting framework, the study decomposes annual GDP per capita growth into segments driven by exogenous TFP evolution versus endogenous capital accumulation fueled by the investment rate ($s_t$). The analysis specifically tests for beta-convergence by regressing the growth rate of GDP per capita on initial TFP levels and government expenditure shares, isolating the extent to which investment endogeneity accelerates or hinders the catch-up process. By exploiting the synthetic panel structure, the study identifies whether the observed growth dispersion is primarily a function of initial productivity heterogeneity or variations in capital accumulation efficiency. This approach rigorously maps the structural Cobb-Douglas parameters ($0.35$ for capital, $0.65$ for labor/human capital) to realized growth outcomes, providing a precise quantification of how policy variables like trade openness modulate the transition to steady-state growth.
\end{IDEA}


